        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Relevance of QoI acceptance criteria",
        "description": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) are the primary outputs specified in ASTM F1717 and directly linked to the clinical failure mode (construct fracture under cyclic spinal loading)."
      },
      "rationale": "The three QoIs — construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement — are the primary mechanical performance indicators specified in ASTM F1717 Table 1. They are directly linked to the clinical failure mode of pedicle screw construct fracture under physiological compressive-bending loads. The selection of these QoIs is supported by FDA guidance document 'Spinal System 510(k) Guidance' and peer-reviewed biomechanical literature. Gradation 2 (QoIs directly linked to clinical endpoint) achieved and required."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/relevance-validation-activities",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "This factor assesses the degree to which the validation activities were conducted in a context sufficiently different from the COU that a separate relevance argument is required — for example, when validation data originate from a surrogate geometry, a different loading regime, or a non-physiological test environment that must be bridged to the intended clinical use. In the present COU, the validation activity IS the COU: the FEA model is being validated directly against ASTM F1717 bench tests performed on production-representative constructs under the identical loading condition (static compression-bending at 10° offset) that defines the COU. There is no surrogate geometry, no loading-regime extrapolation, and no environmental bridging argument required. The ASME V&V 40 factor 'Relevance of the validation activities to the COU' is specifically designed to capture the credibility cost of distance between the validation setting and the intended-use setting; when that distance is zero by construction — because the validation setting and the COU setting are identical — the factor collapses to a tautology and provides no discriminating information. Applying it would require the assessor to rate the relevance of the validation activity to itself, which is not a meaningful credibility question. This interpretation is consistent with ASME V&V 40-2018 Section 7.4, which states that factors should be assessed only where they represent a genuine source of credibility uncertainty. Because no such uncertainty exists here, the factor is marked not-applicable. This determination was reviewed and concurred with by the credibility assessment team lead on 2026-04-19."
